{{fr-verb}}

# {{lb|fr|intransitive}} to [[think]], [[reflect]], [[concentrate]] one's [[mind]] on something {{defdate|late 10th century in ''Passion'', ed. D'Arco Silvio Avalle, 55}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''penser''' tout haut|t=to '''think''' aloud}}
#* '''1845''', Alexandre Dumas, ''La Reine Margot'', vol. I, chap. 4:
#*: {{quote|fr|Je suis incapable de rassembler deux idées ; votre vue m'a ébloui. Je ne '''pense''' plus, j'admire.|t=I am unable to unite two ideas; your aspect has dazzled my mind. I am not '''thinking''' anything any longer, I admire.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1932|author=Louis-Ferdinand Céline|title=Voyage au bout de la nuit
|passage=Vous n'êtes pas venu ici pour '''penser''', mais pour faire les gestes qu'on vous commandera d'exécuter… Nous n'avons pas besoin d'imaginatifs dans notre usine. C'est de chimpanzés dont nous avons besoin…|t=You're not here in order to '''think''', but to do the movements one has told you to perform… We don't need any visionaries in our factory. It's chimpanzees we need…}}
#* '''1992''', David E. Walker, “La pauvreté de la foi”, dans ''Le Québec sceptique'', n° 21 (hiver 1992), p. 32:
#*: {{quote|fr|Ma tâche vise davantage à leur enseigner comment '''penser''' et non que penser. J'espère ainsi que lorsqu'ils auront appris à '''penser''', mes élèves pourront réfléchir par eux-mêmes plutôt que de laisser les autres le faire à leur place.|t=My task is rather aimed at teaching them how to '''think''', not what to think. Having said that, I hope that, when they have learned to '''think''', my pupils will be able to reflect by themselves rather than let others do it in their stead.}}
# {{lb|fr|intransitive}} to [[think]], [[imagine]], [[believe]] {{defdate|late 10th century in ''Passion'', 339}}
#: {{ux|fr|Vous n'en êtes pas où vous '''pensez'''.|t=You are not where you '''think''' you are.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il y a, je '''pense''', dix kilomètres de chez vous chez moi.|t=It is ten kilometres, I '''think''', from your place to my place.}}
#: {{ux|fr|J'irai vous voir demain, je '''pense'''.|t=I will come and see you tomorrow, I '''suppose'''.}}
#: {{ux|fr|La chose n'est pas si facile qu'on le '''pense'''.|t=The thing is not as simple as one might '''believe'''.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je ne '''pensais''' pas que vous vous méprendriez sur le sens de mes paroles.|t=I didn't '''imagine''' you would fail to grasp the meaning of what I said.}}
#* '''1999''', Amélie Nothomb, ''Stupeur et tremblements'', Éditions Albin Michel S. A., p. 11:
#*: {{quote|fr|Je '''pensai''' que j'avais été trop aimable ou familière avec Adam Johnson et je rédigeai un texte froid et distant: […].|t=I '''believed''' I had been too amiable or familiar with Adam Johnson, so I drafted a cold and distant text: […]}}
# {{lb|fr|originally with a ''que'' sentence}} to be of the [[opinion]] that, believe {{defdate|1155 in Wace, ''Brut'', ed. I. Arnold, 263}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je '''pensais''' qu'il était de vos amis.|t=I '''thought''' he was a friend.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je veux être d'accord avec toi, mais je ne '''pense''' pas que nous ayons besoin de son aide.|t=I want to agree with you, but I don't '''think''' we need his help.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je '''pense''' comme vous.|t=I '''agree''' with your view.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il ne dit rien qu'il ne '''pense'''.|t=He doesn't say anything he doesn't '''believe'''.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Dites librement ce que vous '''pensez'''.|t=Cavalierly state your '''opinion'''.}}
#: {{ux|fr|J'espère qu'il ne '''pense''' pas ce qu'il dit.|t=I hope he doesn't '''believe''' what he is saying.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Faites-moi connaître votre façon de '''penser'''.|t=Tell me how you '''think''' about it.}}
#: {{ux|fr|'''Pensez'''-vous ?|t=Do you really '''believe''' that?|footer=(1935, punning at the interlocutor's lack of belief in his own statement)}}
#* '''1945''', Fernand Mitton, ''La Presse française'', vol. 2, chez Guy Le Prat, p. 172:
#*: {{quote|fr|Cette feuille ne craignait pas de dire ce qu'elle '''pensait''', même aux personnages les plus hauts placés.|t=This gazette wasn't afraid to say what it '''thought''', even to persons of the highest ranks.}}
# {{lb|fr|intransitive}} to be [[absorbed]] by a [[worry]] or [[depressing]] [[thought]]s {{defdate|ca. 1160 in ''Éneas'', ed. J.-J. Salverda de Grave, 2221}}
# {{lb|fr|intransitive}} to [[conceive]] a [[project]] {{defdate|c. 1160 in ''Éneas'', 1692}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''de'' + object}} to [[evoke]] the [[image]] or [[remembrance]] of someone in one's mind {{defdate|ca. 1160 in ''Éneas'', 1223}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''penser''' d'aucun}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''à'' + object}} to [[attach]] one's [[thinking]] to someone, especially [[loving]]ly {{defdate|ca. 1165 in ''Troie'', 17621 ds T.-L.}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''Pensez''' à moi.|t='''Think''' of me.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il ne '''pense''' qu'à celle qu'il aime.|t=He '''thinks''' only of his beloved.}}
# {{lb|fr|with infinitive}} to [[believe]] being or doing something {{defdate|ca. 1165 in ''Troie'', 29997 ds T.-L.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il '''pense''' être plus habile que les autres.|t=He '''believes''' he is smarter than others.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il ne '''pensait''' pas être observé.|t=He didn't '''think''' he was being observed.}}
#: {{ux|fr|J'ai '''pensé''' mourir.|t=I '''thought''' I was going to die.}}
#* '''1817''', Marquise Donnissan de Larochejaquelein, ''Mémoires'', L.-G. Michaud, Paris, chap. II, p. 33:
#*: {{quote|fr|Le lendemain '''pensa''' nous être funeste.|The other day '''was to be''' baleful for us. (Note: This impersonal use, even if in use by the classics, is criticized as improper.)}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''mal'' or ''bien'' + ''de'' + object}} to think well or badly, to have a high or low [[opinion]] of someone {{defdate|c. 1170 in Beroul, ''Tristan'', ed. E. Muret, 110}}
#: {{ux|fr|C'est un homme qui '''pense''' toujours mal des autres.|t=He is a man who always '''thinks''' badly of others.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je ne '''pense''' de cette affaire ni bien ni mal.|t=I am indifferent to this affair.|lit=I don't '''think''' either well or badly of this affair.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Que '''pensez'''-vous de cet homme ?|t=What do you '''think''' about this man?}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''de'' + infinitive}} to [[try]] or [[prepare]] to do something {{defdate|1160–74 in Wace, ''Rou'', ed. A. J. Holden, III, 10814}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''penser''' de faire quelque chose|to be '''thinking''' of doing something}}
# {{lb|fr|transitive|reflexive|obsolete}} to reflect on something {{defdate|late 11th century in ''Roland'', ed. J. Bédier, 355}}
#: {{uxi|fr|soi '''penser''' quelque chose}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''à'' + object}} to [[bear]], [[keep]] something in mind, to [[consider]] something {{defdate|c. 1200 in ''Poème moral'', 161a}}
#: {{ux|fr|Le mal vient sans qu'on y '''pense'''.|t=Evil comes without one '''thinking''' of it.}}
#: {{ux|fr|faire ou dire une chose sans '''penser''' à mal|t=to do or say something without '''meaning''' to harm}}
#: {{ux|fr|À quoi '''pensez'''-vous ?|t=What are you '''thinking'''?}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1393|title=Ménagier|editors=G. E. Brereton; J. M. Ferrier|section=I, VI, p. 78
|passage='''Penser''' à mal.|t=To have a bad intention.}}
#* '''2011''', Umberto Eco, ''Le cimetière de Prague'', traduit de l'italien par Jean-Noël Schifano, ed. Grasset, chap. 6:
#*: {{quote|fr|Rebaudengo était une fripouille et, si je '''pense''' à tout ce que j'ai fait après, j'ai l'impression de n'avoir fait des fripouilleries qu'à des fripouilles.|t=Rebaudengo was a rascal, and if I '''think''' of all the things I have done afterwards, I am under the impression of not having played tricks but to rascals.}}
# {{lb|fr|with infinitive}} to [[intend]] to do, [[aim]] at doing something {{defdate|ca. 1200 in ''Hist. Joseph'', 299 ds T.-L.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je '''pensais''' aller vous voir.|t=I '''fancied''' paying you a visit.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Que '''pensez'''-vous faire ?|t=What do you '''intend''' to do?}}
# {{lb|fr|transitive}} to have something in one's mind (c. 1220 in ''Barlaam et Josaphat'', ed. C. Appel, 5623)
#: {{ux|fr|C'est un homme qui ne dit jamais ce qu'il '''pense'''.|t=He's a man who never says what he '''thinks'''.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il '''pense''' beaucoup de choses qu'il ne dit pas.|t=He '''thinks''' a lot of things he doesn't say.}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''à'' + infinitive}} to intend to do, aim to do something {{defdate|1306 in Joinville, ed. N. L. Corbett, § 612}}
#: {{ux|fr|À quoi '''pensez'''-vous de vous conduire ainsi ?|t=What are you '''playing at''' by behaving like this?}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je suis trop de vos amis pour avoir '''pensé''' à vous nuire.|t=I am too much your friend to '''think''' of harming you.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Je '''pensais''' à aller vous voir hier.|t=I '''considered''' visiting you yesterday.}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''mal''|obsolete}} to intend to do something bad {{defdate|15th century in ''Isopet III de Paris'', ed. J. Bastin, vol. 2, p. 401}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''penser''' mal}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''à'' + object}} to [[take care]] of {{defdate|from 1636, in Monet}}
#: {{ux|fr|Il nous a reçus admirablement, il a '''pensé''' à tout.|t=He has welcomed us admirably, he has '''thought''' of everything.}}
# {{lb|fr|with ''bien''|in politics, religion, moral}} to have opinions in [[accordance]] with the [[agreed]] [[principles]] {{defdate|1823, in ''Courier''}}
#: {{uxi|fr|bien '''penser'''}}
# {{lb|fr|with adverb or adverbial expression}} to have a certain [[intellectual]] [[tendency]], [[preference]] or [[property]]
#: {{ux|fr|'''penser''' finement, noblement, singulièrement, hardiment|t=to '''think''' finely, nobly, in a singular way, boldly}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''penser''' avec justesse.|t=to '''think''' with accuracy}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''penser''' juste|t=to '''think''' in the right way, to be [[right-thinking]]}}

====Usage notes====
Today ''penser'' is commonly construed in one of the following ways:
* "penser que ''proposition''" — "to think (that) ''clause''". (Note: The ''que'' is mandatory.)
:When ''penser'' is in the negative or interrogative, the clause after ''que'' takes a verb in the subjunctive. If it is in the affirmative, it takes the indicative. In spoken French, the interrogative also tends to be followed by the indicative.
:* "Je pense qu'il est parti." — "I think (that) he's left."
:* "Je ne pense pas qu'il soit parti." — "I don't think (that) he's left."
* "penser à ''substantif''" — "to think about ''noun''".
** "Je pense à mon frère." — "I'm thinking about my brother."
** "Je pense à elle." — "I'm thinking about her." (''Not'' *"Je lui pense.")
* "penser ''adverbe'' [''especially ''[[bien]] = well'', ''[[mal]] = ill] de ''substantif''" — "to think ''adverb'' of ''noun''". (Note: in questions, the adverb is represented by ''[[que]]'', not by ''[[comment]]'' as might be expected.)
** "Je pense très bien de lui." — "I think very well of him."
** "Qu'est-ce que tu en penses ?" — "What do you think of it?"
* "penser ''infinitif''" — "to think one will ''bare infinitive''".
** "Je pense y aller demain." — "I think I'll go there tomorrow."
* "penser à ''infinitif''" — "to think about ''gerund''".
** "Je pense à y aller demain." — "I'm thinking about going there tomorrow."

